"],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen de Yarnewek was born in 1330, in Londesborough, Yorkshire, England, her father, Thomas de Yarnewek, was 30 and her mother, Alice Senlis, was 30. She married William de Bromflete in 1371, in Londesborough, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1396, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1330–1396":"1330–1396","1330–1410":"1330–1410","1372–1430":"1372–1430","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1300–1374":"1300–1374","13 January 1374":"13. jaanuar 1374","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","130